Parse tree contains actual token /values/ - concrete lexemes and additional information (whatever you deem necessary adding). Token represents lexical unit found in input data. ExpectedToken describes required token category and OPTIONAL lexeme value.

Imports

parse_primitives

Types

LexInfo = object
  pos*: int                    ## Position of *token* in original lexer stream
Predefined type for Info field in token. Default implementation provided most common features. It is recommended but not mandatory to use this type for third generic parameter in Token. 
ETokKind = enum
  etokRegular, etokEOF
Token[Category; Lexeme; Info] = object
  case kind*: ETokKind
  of etokRegular:
      cat*: Category           ## Token category. It is REQUIRED to be correct
                   ## as it is always used in parsing
      lex*: Lexeme             ## Lexeme information. It OPTIONAL and might be
                 ## used in parsing.
      info*: Info              ## Additional information in token. It is OPTIONAL
                ## and never used in parsing.
    
  of etokEOF:
      nil
Actual value of input token 
LexPredicate[L] = proc (l: L): bool {...}{.noSideEffect.}
ExpectedToken[C; L] = object
  case kind*: ETokKind
  of etokRegular:
      cat*: C                  ## Expected token category
      case hasLex*: bool        ## Whether or not lexeme value should be
                      ## considered
      of true:
          case isPredicate*: bool
          of false:
              lex*: L          ## Expected lexeme value
            
          of true:
              lexPred*: LexPredicate[L]
              lexPredRepr*: string
              lexPredLiteral*: string

        
      of false:
          nil

    
  of etokEOF:
      nil
Description of token to expect during parsing. In order for input token to match category MUST be identical (equality comparison). In case hasLex is true lexeme values also MUST match. 
NoCategory = enum
  catNoCategory
Enum to describe token 'without' category - mostly used in examples when parsing sequences string. 
LexSet[L] = object
  hasAll: bool                 ## Whether or not all lexeme values are in set
  lexemes: HashSet[L]
  predicates: seq[LexPredicate[L]]
Set of lexemes 
EofTok = object
TokSet[C; L] = object
  tokens: Table[C, LexSet[L]] ## Map from
                           ## token category to list of expected lexemes + whether or not
                           ## token can be accepted if lexeme does not match.
  hasEof: bool
Set of expected tokens + EOF token (end of inptu sequence) 
LexLookup[L] = object
  table: Table[L, seq[int]]     ## Expected tokens with concrete lexeme
                         ## specified
  hasAll: seq[int]             ## Expected tokens without specification for
                 ## lexeme
  predicates: seq[tuple[pr: LexPredicate[L], altid: int]]
Lookup table from lexemes to one or more parsing alternatives 
TokLookup[C; L] = object
  table: Table[C, LexLookup[L]]

LinePosInfo = object
  line*: int
  column*: int
  filename*: string
